  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **unlawful** in virtually all jurisdictions worldwide. It is a criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money (often derived from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or organized crime) to make it appear legitimate. \n\n### **Why is Money Laundering Illegal?**\n1. **Facilitation of Crime**: It enables criminals to profit from illegal activities and reinvest those profits into further criminal enterprises.  \n2. **Economic Harm**: It undermines the integrity of financial systems, distorts markets, and can destabilize economies.  \n3. **Social Impact**: It perpetuates corruption, funds terrorism, and harms society by enabling harmful criminal activities.\n\n### **Laws and Enforcement**\nMost countries have **anti-money laundering (AML) laws** in place, often aligned with international standards set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. Penalties for money laundering can include **fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture**. \n\nIf you have questions or concerns about this topic, it\u2019s advisable to consult legal professionals or compliance experts.",
